{{italic title}}
[[File:Shuowen-子.png|thumb|right|upright|The ''Shuowen Jiezi'' entry for ''zǐ'' 子 "child", showing the [[Small Seal Script|small seal]] form (top right), with the "ancient script" and ''Zhòuwén'' forms on the left{{sfn|Qiu|2000|p=73}}]]
The '''''Shizhoupian''''' ({{zh|c=史籀篇|p=Shǐzhòupiān}}) was an early dictionary of [[Chinese character]]s written in the [[Great Seal script]].  The work was traditionally dated to the reign of [[King Xuan of Zhou]] (827–782 BCE), but many modern scholars assign it to the [[State of Qin]] in the [[Warring States period]].  It is now known only through fragments.

The '''''Zhòuwén''''' ({{lang|zh|籀文}}) are 220 or so examples of ancient characters from the ''Shizhoupian'' quoted in the [[Han dynasty]] character dictionary ''[[Shuowen Jiezi]]''.{{sfn|Qiu|2000|p=72}}
The ''zhòuwén'' characters have been described as generally symmetrical and balanced, and are on average (although not always) more complex than the later seal characters.{{sfn|Qiu|2000|p=74}} They contain many swirls and circles in place of later squared or rectilinear forms.

According to the postface of the ''Shuowen Jiezi'' and the "Treatise on Literature" chapter of the ''[[Book of Han]]'', the work was written during the reign of the late [[Western Zhou]] king Xuan by Shǐ Zhòu ({{lang|zh|史籀}} "Historian Zhou"), and consisted of 15 chapters ({{lang|zh|篇}} ''piān'').{{sfn|Galambos|2006|pp=154–155}}

[[Wang Guowei]] disputed this account in his commentary on the ''Shizhoupian'', arguing that the structure and style of the characters did not match inscriptions from the period.{{sfn|Qiu|2000|pp=72–77}} Wang also questioned the traditional interpretation of ''zhòu'' ({{lang|zh|籀}}) as the historian's name, pointing out that in ancient times, according to the ''Shuowen'', it had the same meaning as {{lang|zh-Hant|讀}} ''dú'' ("to study and understand the meaning of books; to read"). According to this view, the title of the book was likely taken from the first sentence of the text (as is often done when assigning names to untitled ancient texts like those on bronzes), which presumably contained "the historian studies...".{{sfn|Qiu|2000|p=74}}{{sfn|Chén|2003|p=17}}<ref>''Hànyǔ Dà Zìdiǎn'' pp. 1677, 1259.</ref>

Tang Lan identified Shǐ Zhoù (Historian Zhòu) with Shǐ Liú ({{lang|zh|史留}} "Historian Liú"), a name written with a similar character in the ''Book of Han'' chapter on "Notable Persons Past and Present" covering the [[Spring and Autumn period|Spring and Autumn]] and Warring States periods.{{sfn|Qiu|2000|p=74}} A Historian Liú from the correct period is mentioned on an ancient ''dǐng'' tripodal cauldron in the collection of the [[Shanghai Museum]].{{sfn|Chén|2003|pp=17–19}}

