{{infobox Museum |name= '''Sutherland Steam Mill Museum''' |image= SutherlandSteamMill_2018.jpg |established= 1970 |location= [[Denmark, Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]] |type = mill museum |director = |curator = |visitors = |website = [http://sutherlandsteammill.novascotia.ca/ sutherlandsteammill.novascotia.ca] }}
The '''Sutherland Steam Mill Museum''' is a restored steam woodworking mill from the 1890s located in [[Denmark, Nova Scotia]]. The mill operated until 1958. Today it is part of the [[Nova Scotia Museum]] system.
The museum represents the transition from water powered mills, such as that preserved at the nearby [[Balmoral Grist Mill Museum]], to the more powerful and efficient [[steam mill|steam-driven mill]]. The mill was located in at the centre of a vast woodland area and was situated next to a railroad. Thus it had excellent access to both raw materials and to markets though shipping terminals at [[Pictou]] and [[Wallace, Nova Scotia|Wallace]]. At its peak, the mill employed more than a dozen workers, and it produced sawn lumber, sleds and carriages, sashes and doors and other architectural products such as [[Victorian architecture#North America|gingerbread]]. The founder of the mill, Alexander Sutherland retired in 1940 and his son and successor Wilfred Sutherland retired in 1958. The mill became a museum in 1970 and it was adopted into the Nova Scotia Museum Complex in 1975.<ref>Sutherland Steam Mill (brochure) n.d, Nova Scotia Museum Complex</ref>
The museum lies next to the Shortline Railbed section of the [[Trans-Canada Trail]]. The Museum offers free bike loans for day use on the trail.<ref>[https://sutherlandsteammill.novascotia.ca/borrow-bike-trail-program Sutherland Steam Mill "Borrow a Bike" program]. Accessed July 8, 2018.</ref> It also offers free woodworking space within the museum.<ref>[https://sutherlandsteammill.novascotia.ca/maker-space Sutherland Steam Mill Maker Space]. Accessed July 8, 2018.</ref>
